SwiftAgg+: Achieving Asymptotically Optimal Communication Loads in Secure Aggregation for Federated Learning

Tayyebeh Jahani-Nezhad Mohammad Ali Maddah-Ali Songze Li Giuseppe Caire T. Jahani-Nezhad and G. Caire are with the Electrical Engineering and Computer Science Department, Technische Universität Berlin, 10587 Berlin, Germany (e-mail: t.jahani.nezhad@tu-berlin.de, caire@tu-berlin.de) T. Jahani-Nezhad and M. A. Maddah-ali are with the Department of Electrical Engineering, Sharif University of Technology, Tehran 11365-11155, Iran (e-mail: maddah_ali@sharif.edu)S. Li is with IoT Thrust, The Hong Kong University of Science and Technology (Guangzhou), and Department of Computer Science and Engineering, The Hong Kong University of Science and Technology (e-mail:songzeli@ust.hk)The work of T. Jahani-Nezhad and G. Caire was partially funded by the European Research Council under the ERC Advanced Grant N. 789190, CARENET.
Abstract

We propose SwiftAgg+, a novel secure aggregation protocol for federated learning systems, where a central server aggregates local models of N∈ℕ𝑁ℕN\in\mathbb{N} distributed users, each of size L∈ℕ𝐿ℕL\in\mathbb{N}, trained on their local data, in a privacy-preserving manner. SwiftAgg+ can significantly reduce the communication overheads without any compromise on security, and achieve optimal communication loads within diminishing gaps. Specifically, in presence of at most D=o​(N)𝐷𝑜𝑁D=o(N) dropout users, SwiftAgg+ achieves a per-user communication load of (1+𝒪​(1N))​L1𝒪1𝑁𝐿(1+\mathcal{O}(\frac{1}{N}))L symbols and a server communication load of (1+𝒪​(1N))​L1𝒪1𝑁𝐿(1+\mathcal{O}(\frac{1}{N}))L symbols, with a worst-case information-theoretic security guarantee, against any subset of up to T=o​(N)𝑇𝑜𝑁T=o(N) semi-honest users who may also collude with the curious server. Moreover, the proposed SwiftAgg+ allows for a flexible trade-off between communication loads and the number of active communication links. In particular, for T<N−D𝑇𝑁𝐷T<N-D and for any K∈ℕ𝐾ℕK\in\mathbb{N}, SwiftAgg+ can achieve the server communication load of (1+TK)​L1𝑇𝐾𝐿(1+\frac{T}{K})L symbols, and per-user communication load of up to (1+T+DK)​L1𝑇𝐷𝐾𝐿(1+\frac{T+D}{K})L symbols, where the number of pair-wise active connections in the network is N2​(K+T+D+1)𝑁2𝐾𝑇𝐷1\frac{N}{2}(K+T+D+1).

Index Terms:
Federated learning, Secure aggregation, Secret sharing, Dropout resiliency, Optimal communication load.

I Introduction

Federated learning (FL) is an emerging distributed learning framework that allows a group of distributed users (e.g., mobile devices) to collaboratively train a global model of size L𝐿L with their local private data, without sharing the data [1, 2, 3]. Specifically, in a FL system with a central server and N𝑁N users, during each training iteration, the server sends the current state of the global model to the users. Receiving the global model, each user then trains a local model with its local data, and sends the local model to the server. By aggregating the local models, the server can update the global model for the next iteration. While the local datasets are not directly shared with the server, several studies have shown that a curious server can launch model inversion attacks to reveal information about the training data of individual users from their local models (see, e.g., [4, 5]). Therefore, the key challenge to protect users’ data privacy is to design secure aggregation protocols, which allow the aggregation of local models to be computed without revealing each individual model even if the server colludes with a limited number of users, called semi-honest users, in the system. Moreover, as some users may randomly drop out of the aggregation process (due to low batteries or unstable connections), the server should be able to robustly recover the aggregated local models of the surviving users in a privacy-preserving manner.

As such motivated, a secure aggregation protocol SecAgg is proposed in [6]. In SecAgg, each pair of users agree on a shared random vector. In addition, each user generates a private random vector and secret shares it with other users. Before sending its local model to the server, each user masks the local model in a particular way. The mask is created based on the private and shared random vectors such that the shared part can be canceled out when aggregated at the server. In order to recover the result and cancel the remaining masks, the private random vector of each surviving user and the shared random vectors of each dropped user must be reconstructed using the collected shares from surviving users in the second round of communication.

Note that to have an information-theoretic security, the shared and the private random vectors must be chosen uniformly at random from vectors of size L𝐿L. However, to make it practical in SecAgg, it is assumed that the users agree on common seeds for a pseudo-random generator rather than on the entire shared random vectors which is not secure in the context of information theory. In this paper, we focus on information-theoretic security guarantees.

One of the major challenges for SecAgg to scale up is the communication load. The secret sharing among users requires all-to-all communication, which incurs quadratic cost in the number of users N𝑁N. There has been a series of works that aim to improve the communication efficiency of SecAgg (see, e.g., [7, 8, 9]). In [7], TurboAgg is proposed to perform secure aggregation following a circular topology, achieving a communication load of 𝒪​(L​N​log⁡N)𝒪𝐿𝑁𝑁\mathcal{O}(LN\log N) at the server and 𝒪​(L​log⁡N)𝒪𝐿𝑁\mathcal{O}(L\log N) at each user. The idea of TurboAgg is partitioning the users into several groups each of size 𝒪​(log⁡N)𝒪𝑁\mathcal{O}(\log N) to accelerate model aggregation phase. To protect individual models, each user masks its local model in a particular way. Furthermore, the masked local models are encoded using Lagrange coded computing [10] such that the data of dropped users can be recovered at each stage of the protocol. Each user in a group computes the aggregation of the masked models and the aggregation of coded models of all users in the previous groups, and sends them to all users in the next group, as well as the masked and coded version of its model. The missing terms of aggregated masked models, caused by the dropped users, can be recovered in the next group if at least half of the users in a group do not drop out. TurboAgg guarantees the privacy of individual local models with high probability as long as the number of semi-honest users is less than N/2𝑁2N/2.

In [8], SecAgg+ is proposed which considers a k𝑘k-regular communication graph among users instead of the complete graph used in SecAgg to reduce the communication and computation loads, where k=𝒪​(log⁡N)𝑘𝒪𝑁k=\mathcal{O}(\log N). It means that each user secret shares with a subset of other users instead of sharing with all of them. It is shown that SecAgg+ requires a communication of 𝒪​(L​N+N​log⁡N)𝒪𝐿𝑁𝑁𝑁\mathcal{O}(LN+N\log N) at the server and 𝒪​(L+log⁡N)𝒪𝐿𝑁\mathcal{O}(L+\log N) at each user. In [9], another similar idea, CCESA, is proposed in which a sparse random graph is used as communication network instead of the complete graph. Thus, secret sharing is used for a subset of users instead of all-to-all communication. While SecAgg+, TurboAgg and CCESA improve the communication efficiency of SecAgg, they only provide probabilistic privacy guarantees as opposed to the worst-case guarantee of SecAgg.

Some other secure aggregation protocols focus on reducing the computation complexity of SecAgg, rather than the communication load. FastSecAgg is proposed in [11] which presents a multi-secret sharing scheme based on a finite field version of the Fast Fourier Transform to achieve a trade-off between the number of secrets, the dropout tolerance and the privacy threshold. FastSecAgg reduces the computation load of the server as well as per-user to 𝒪​(L​log⁡N)𝒪𝐿𝑁\mathcal{O}(L\log N), while achieves the same order of communication as SecAgg with lower privacy threshold and dropout tolerance.

In  [12], LightSecAgg is proposed to reduce the computation complexity bottleneck in secure aggregation. In LightSecAgg, each user independently samples a random mask, encodes it using T𝑇T-private MDS (maximum distance separable) coding, generating secret shares of the mask to send to other users. Then, each user adds mask to its local model and sends the masked model to the server. The server can reconstruct and cancel out the aggregated mask of surviving users via a one-shot decoding, using the aggregated coded masks received in a second phase of communication with surviving users. Similar idea of one-shot reconstruction of aggregated mask was also utilized in [13], which nevertheless requires a trusted third party, and much more randomness needs to be generated, as well as more storage at each user.

As an earlier and conference version of this manuscript, in [14] , we propose SwiftAgg which reduces the server communication load via partitioning users into several groups and using Shamir’s secret sharing [15] to keep the local models private. SwiftAgg is able to achieve correct aggregation in presence of up to D𝐷D dropout users, with formally-proven the worst-case security guarantee against up to T𝑇T semi-honest users. Independently, similar ideas have been used in CodedSecAgg [16], but dropout users in groups have not been addressed and there is no formal definition and proof of privacy. The communication loads and the computation loads of the existing approaches are compared in Table I.

In this paper, we propose SwiftAgg+ as a new scheme for secure aggregation in federated learning, which is robust against up to D𝐷D user dropouts and achieves worst-case security guarantees against up to T<N−D𝑇𝑁𝐷T<N-D semi-honest users which may collude with each other as well as with the server to gain some information. In SwiftAgg+, in order to compute the aggregation of local models in a privacy-preserving manner, the number of symbols received by the server is (1+𝒪​(1N))​L1𝒪1𝑁𝐿(1+\mathcal{O}(\frac{1}{N}))L as long as T=o​(N)𝑇𝑜𝑁T=o(N) and N−D=𝒪​(N)𝑁𝐷𝒪𝑁N-D=\mathcal{O}(N). In addition, the number of symbols sent by each user is (1+𝒪​(1N))​L1𝒪1𝑁𝐿(1+\mathcal{O}(\frac{1}{N}))L, for T=o​(N)𝑇𝑜𝑁T=o(N) and D=o​(N)𝐷𝑜𝑁D=o(N).

Moreover, since in federated learning many of the users may not be accessible from each other, the number of active communication links, among users or from users to the server, is also an important factor when designing secure aggregation protocols. SwiftAgg+ allows for a flexible trade-off between the communication loads and the network connections. To achieve this trade-off, we first partition the users into groups of size T+D+K𝑇𝐷𝐾T+D+K for some K∈ℕ𝐾ℕK\in\mathbb{N} (See Fig. 4), and the groups are arranged on an arbitrary hierarchical tree with the server as the root. Then in the first phase, each user partitions its local model into K𝐾K parts. In the second phase, users within each group secret share the partitions of their local models using ramp secret sharing [17], and aggregate the shares locally. In the third phase, each user aggregates in-group shares and the messages received from the corresponding users in its children groups and sends the result to the corresponding user in its parent group, which is finally sent to the server. In the third phase, if one user in a group drops out, the rest of the users in the sequence that includes the dropped user remain silent. This aggregation tree provides flexibility to adjust the delay of each iteration of training process based on the network connections. Additionally, parameter K𝐾K controls the trade-off between communication loads and network connectivity which can be chosen based on the constraints of the network.

SwiftAgg+ simultaneously achieves the following advantages compared to the existing works:

  1. 1.

    For T=o​(N)𝑇𝑜𝑁T=o(N) and N−D=𝒪​(N)𝑁𝐷𝒪𝑁N-D=\mathcal{O}(N), the server communication load in SwiftAgg+ is within factor 1 of the cut-set lower bound.

  2. 2.

    SwiftAgg+ has the flexibility to reduce the number of active connections between the users at the cost of increasing the communication load away from the optimum.

  3. 3.

    It is resilient to up to D𝐷D user dropouts. As opposed to the existing schemes, in SwiftAgg+, due to the structure of the scheme, the effects of user dropouts are already handled in one round of communication with the server, and there is no need to take place another round of communication.

  4. 4.

    It achieves worst-case information-theoretic security against a curious server and any subset of up to T<N−D𝑇𝑁𝐷T<N-D semi-honest users.

  5. 5.

    Based on the possible connections among users, SwiftAgg+ have a flexibility to control the delay of each training iteration.

Meanwhile, similar as LightSecAgg, the proposed SwiftAgg+ also enjoys small server computation complexity with worst-cast security guarantees.

For an achievable scheme 𝒜​(N,T,D)𝒜𝑁𝑇𝐷\mathscr{A}(N,T,D) for secure aggregation problem, consisting of N𝑁N users and a server, we define the undirected communication graph 𝒢𝒜​(𝒱,ℰ𝒜)subscript𝒢𝒜𝒱subscriptℰ𝒜\mathscr{G}_{\mathscr{A}}(\mathcal{V},\mathcal{E}_{\mathscr{A}}). In this graph, 𝒱={U1,…,UN,server}𝒱subscript𝑈1…subscript𝑈𝑁server\mathcal{V}=\{U_{1},\ldots,U_{N},\textsf{server}\} is the set of vertices representing users and the server, and ℰ𝒜subscriptℰ𝒜\mathcal{E}_{\mathscr{A}} is the set of the edges corresponding to active communication links among these vertices. In this graph, edge e∈ℰ𝒜𝑒subscriptℰ𝒜e\in\mathcal{E}_{\mathscr{A}} between two vertices v1,v2∈𝒱subscript𝑣1subscript𝑣2𝒱v_{1},v_{2}\in\mathcal{V} exists if the corresponding users communicate directly with each other (they do not send null message ⟂perpendicular-to\perp).

III Main results

In this section, we present our main results on per-user and server communication loads, achieved by the proposed SwiftAgg+ scheme. Note that the operations are done in a finite field, which is large enough to avoid hitting the boundary in the process of aggregation. We choose a finite field G​F​(p)𝐺𝐹𝑝GF(p) denoted by 𝔽psubscript𝔽𝑝\mathbb{F}_{p}, for some prime number p𝑝p, where N​(ℓ−1)<p≤2​N​(ℓ−1)𝑁ℓ1𝑝2𝑁ℓ1N(\ell-1)<p\leq 2N(\ell-1).

Theorem 1.

Consider a secure aggregation problem, with N𝑁N users and one server, where up to T𝑇T users are semi-honest and up to D𝐷D users may drop out. There is an achievable scheme which need

Rserver=(1+TN−T−D),subscript𝑅server1𝑇𝑁𝑇𝐷\displaystyle R_{\text{server}}=\left(1+\frac{T}{N-T-D}\right), (3)
Ruser≤(1+T+DN−T−D),subscript𝑅user1𝑇𝐷𝑁𝑇𝐷\displaystyle\ R_{\text{user}}\leq\left(1+\frac{T+D}{N-T-D}\right),

symbols from 𝔽psubscript𝔽𝑝\mathbb{F}_{p}.

Proof.

The proof can be found in Section VI-A. ∎

To achieve the communication loads of (3) in Theorem 1, we propose SwiftAgg+, a novel secure aggregation scheme in federated learning. In SwiftAgg+, under the condition of T=o​(N)𝑇𝑜𝑁T=o(N) and D=o​(N)𝐷𝑜𝑁D=o(N), the number of symbols sent by each user is (1+𝒪​(1N))​L1𝒪1𝑁𝐿(1+\mathcal{O}(\frac{1}{N}))L and the number of symbols received by the server is (1+𝒪​(1N))​L1𝒪1𝑁𝐿(1+\mathcal{O}(\frac{1}{N}))L in order to compute the aggregation of local models in a privacy-preserving manner. In other words, for large N𝑁N, the communication load per user tends to L𝐿L symbols from 𝔽psubscript𝔽𝑝\mathbb{F}_{p} and the total communication load of the server also tends to L𝐿L symbols from 𝔽psubscript𝔽𝑝\mathbb{F}_{p}.

Theorem 2.

For T=o​(N)𝑇𝑜𝑁T=o(N) and N−D=𝒪​(N)𝑁𝐷𝒪𝑁N-D=\mathcal{O}(N), in terms of the number of required bits, the server communication load in SwiftAgg+ is within factor 1 of the cut-set lower bound.

Proof.

The proof can be found in Section VI-C. ∎

Theorem 3.

For local models with uniform distributions, in terms of the number of required bits, the per-user communication load in SwiftAgg+ is within factor logℓ⁡ℓ​Nsubscriptℓℓ𝑁\log_{\ell}{\ell N} of the cut-set lower bound, for T=o​(N)𝑇𝑜𝑁T=o(N) and D=o​(N)𝐷𝑜𝑁D=o(N).

Proof.

The proof can be found in Section VI-D. ∎

Remark 1:

Note that the case T=o​(N)𝑇𝑜𝑁T=o(N) is well justified. Restricted with a limited budget, it often becomes prohibitively difficult for the adversary to hack a constant fraction of the users as the number of users grows. For example, it is seems easier to hack one of only two users rather than 50 out of 100 ones.

As the number of active communication links is important in federated learning, SwiftAgg+ also allows us to reduce the number of active network connections in the secure aggregation problem at the cost of increasing the communication load away from the optimum. The result is presented in the following theorem.

Theorem 4.

Consider a secure aggregation problem, with N𝑁N users and one server, where up to T𝑇T users are semi-honest and up to D𝐷D users may drop out. For any K∈ℕ𝐾ℕK\in\mathbb{N}, where (T+D+K)|Nconditional𝑇𝐷𝐾𝑁(T+D+K)|N, there exist an achievable scheme 𝒜K​(N,T,D)subscript𝒜𝐾𝑁𝑇𝐷{\mathscr{A}_{K}}(N,T,D) with

Rserver(𝒜K)superscriptsubscript𝑅serversubscript𝒜𝐾\displaystyle R_{\text{server}}^{(\mathscr{A}_{K})} =1+TK,absent1𝑇𝐾\displaystyle=1+\frac{T}{K}, (4)
Ruser(𝒜K)superscriptsubscript𝑅usersubscript𝒜𝐾\displaystyle R_{\text{user}}^{(\mathscr{A}_{K})} ≤(1+T+DK),absent1𝑇𝐷𝐾\displaystyle\leq\left(1+\frac{T+D}{K}\right),

symbols from 𝔽psubscript𝔽𝑝\mathbb{F}_{p}. The communication graph of this achievable scheme 𝒢𝒜K​(𝒱,ℰ𝒜K)subscript𝒢subscript𝒜𝐾𝒱subscriptℰsubscript𝒜𝐾\mathscr{G}_{\mathscr{A}_{K}}(\mathcal{V},\mathcal{E}_{\mathscr{A}_{K}}) consists of |ℰ𝒜K|=N2​(K+T+D+1)subscriptℰsubscript𝒜𝐾𝑁2𝐾𝑇𝐷1|\mathcal{E}_{\mathscr{A}_{K}}|=\frac{N}{2}(K+T+D+1) edges.

Proof.

The proof can be found in Section VI-A. ∎

Remark 2:

In (4) by increasing parameter K𝐾K, both per-user communication load and server communication load are reduced, while the number of active connections in the achievable scheme |ℰ𝒜K|subscriptℰsubscript𝒜𝐾|\mathcal{E}_{\mathscr{A}_{K}}| is increased and vice versa. This allows us to have a flexible trade-off between communication loads and the complexity of the communication pattern (in terms of number of active links).

To achieve the trade-off between communication loads and network connections |ℰ𝒜K|subscriptℰsubscript𝒜𝐾|\mathcal{E}_{\mathscr{A}_{K}}|, SwiftAgg+ partitions the users into some disjoint groups, each of size K+D+T𝐾𝐷𝑇K+D+T users labeled as user 111 to user K+D+T𝐾𝐷𝑇K+D+T of that group. The NK+D+T𝑁𝐾𝐷𝑇\frac{N}{K+D+T} groups are arranged in an arbitrary tree with the server as the root. The model aggregation starts from the leaves of the tree, and proceeds in three main phases: Phase 1: Each user partitions the vector of its local model of length L𝐿L into K𝐾K sub-vectors of length LK𝐿𝐾\frac{L}{K}, Phase 2: Each user uses a ramp sharing [17] to share the sub-vectors of its model to other users within its group, Phase 3: Each user aggregates the shares that it receives in Phase 2 and also adds it to the messages received from the corresponding users in its children groups and sends the result to the corresponding user in its parent group. These messages are finally reach to the server and are used to recover the aggregated local models.

Remark 3:

The minimum communication loads in Theorem 1 are achieved by setting K𝐾K to its maximum value of N−D−T𝑁𝐷𝑇N-D-T. The minimum number of communication connections is achieved by setting K=1𝐾1K=1, which reduces to the SwiftAgg scheme in [14].

Remark 4:

While in problem formulation we let L→∞→𝐿L\to\infty, the proposed scheme works for finite values of L𝐿L, where K|Lconditional𝐾𝐿K|L. If K∤Lnot-divides𝐾𝐿K\nmid L, we can zero-pad the local models.

    Inter-group Communication and Aggregation: In this phase, user (1,t)1𝑡(1,t), t∈[6]𝑡delimited-[]6t\in[6], calculates message 𝐒(1,t)=𝐐(1,t)subscript𝐒1𝑡subscript𝐐1𝑡\mathbf{S}_{(1,t)}~{}=~{}\mathbf{Q}_{(1,t)}, and it to user (2,t)2𝑡(2,t).

    User (2,t)2𝑡(2,t), t∈[6]𝑡delimited-[]6t\in[6], calculates message 𝐒(2,t)=𝐒(1,t)+𝐐(2,t)subscript𝐒2𝑡subscript𝐒1𝑡subscript𝐐2𝑡\mathbf{S}_{(2,t)}=\mathbf{S}_{(1,t)}+\mathbf{Q}_{(2,t)}, upon receiving 𝐒(1,t)subscript𝐒1𝑡\mathbf{S}_{(1,t)}. If user (2,t)2𝑡(2,t) does not receive 𝐒(1,t)subscript𝐒1𝑡\mathbf{S}_{(1,t)}, it also remains silent for the rest of the protocol. In this particular example that user 3 drops out, it sends no message to user 9, and thus user 9 also remains silent.

  5. 5.

    Communication with the Server: User t𝑡t of the last group, i.e., user (2,t)2𝑡(2,t) sends 𝐒(2,t)subscript𝐒2𝑡\mathbf{S}_{(2,t)} to the server, for t∈[6]𝑡delimited-[]6t\in[6]. Clearly in this example, user 9 remains silent and sends nothing (or null message ⟂perpendicular-to\perp) to the server.

  6. 6.

    Recovering the result: Let us define

    +x3​∑n=1n≠312𝐙~n,1+x4​∑n=1n≠312𝐙~n,2.superscript𝑥3superscriptsubscript𝑛1𝑛312subscript~𝐙𝑛1superscript𝑥4superscriptsubscript𝑛1𝑛312subscript~𝐙𝑛2\displaystyle+x^{3}\sum_{\begin{subarray}{c}n=1\\ n\neq 3\end{subarray}}^{12}\tilde{\mathbf{Z}}_{n,1}+x^{4}\sum_{\begin{subarray}{c}n=1\\ n\neq 3\end{subarray}}^{12}\tilde{\mathbf{Z}}_{n,2}.

    One can verify that 𝐒(2,t)subscript𝐒2𝑡\mathbf{S}_{(2,t)}, for t=1,2,4,5,6𝑡12456t=1,2,4,5,6 that are received by the server are indeed equal to 𝐅​(αt)𝐅subscript𝛼𝑡\mathbf{F}(\alpha_{t}), for t=1,2,4,5,6𝑡12456t=1,2,4,5,6.

    Since 𝐅​(x)𝐅𝑥\mathbf{F}(x) is a polynomial function of degree 4, based on Lagrange interpolation rule the server can recover all the coefficients of this polynomial using the outcomes of 5 users which are not dropped. Thus, the server is able to recover the aggregation of local models of surviving users, i.e., ∑n=1n≠312𝐖nsuperscriptsubscript𝑛1𝑛312subscript𝐖𝑛\sum_{\begin{subarray}{c}n=1\\ n\neq 3\end{subarray}}^{12}\mathbf{W}_{n} and the correctness constraint is satisfied.

In this example, the per-user communication load is 2​L2𝐿2L and the server communication load is 53​L53𝐿\frac{5}{3}L. In addition, the communication graph has 42 edges with 13 vertices, where because of user dropouts no communication occurs on 7 edges. As compared to Example 1, the communication load is increased while the the number of connections among users are decreased. The number of connections can be minimized by choosing ν=T+D+1=4𝜈𝑇𝐷14\nu=T+D+1=4 and having three groups, where no partitioning of local models is performed.

V The Proposed SwiftAgg+ Scheme

In this section, we formally describe the proposed SwiftAgg+, which introduces a trade-off between the communication loads and the number of active communication links among users and the server. Consider a network consisting of one server and N𝑁N users, U1,U2,…,UNsubscript𝑈1subscript𝑈2…subscript𝑈𝑁U_{1},U_{2},\dots,U_{N}, where up to T𝑇T of them are semi-honest which may collude with each other or with the server to gain some information about other users’ local models. Furthermore, up to D𝐷D users may drop out, and their indices are denoted by 𝒟𝒟\mathcal{D}. The operations need to be done in a finite field, which is large enough to avoid hitting the boundary in the process of aggregation. We choose a finite field G​F​(p)𝐺𝐹𝑝GF(p) denoted by 𝔽psubscript𝔽𝑝\mathbb{F}_{p}, for some prime number p𝑝p. Each user n𝑛n has a local model 𝐖n∈𝔽pLsubscript𝐖𝑛superscriptsubscript𝔽𝑝𝐿\mathbf{W}_{n}\in\mathbb{F}_{p}^{L} and a set of random variables 𝒵n={𝐙n,j,j∈[T]}subscript𝒵𝑛subscript𝐙𝑛𝑗𝑗delimited-[]𝑇\mathcal{Z}_{n}=\{\mathbf{Z}_{n,j},j\in[T]\} whose elements are chosen independently and uniformly at random from 𝔽pLKsuperscriptsubscript𝔽𝑝𝐿𝐾\mathbb{F}_{p}^{\frac{L}{K}}, for some parameter K∈ℕ𝐾ℕK\in\mathbb{N} such that (T+D+K)|Nconditional𝑇𝐷𝐾𝑁(T+D+K)|N. The server wants to recover the aggregated local models of the surviving users, i.e., 𝐖=∑n∈[N]\𝒟𝐖n𝐖subscript𝑛\delimited-[]𝑁𝒟subscript𝐖𝑛\mathbf{W}=\sum_{n\in[N]\backslash\mathcal{D}}\mathbf{W}_{n}, while the individual models remain private from semi-honest users and the server. To reach this goal, SwiftAgg+ takes the following steps.

1) Grouping: The set of N𝑁N users are arbitrarily partitioned into ΓΓ\Gamma groups, each of size ν≜D+T+K≜𝜈𝐷𝑇𝐾\nu\triangleq D+T+K, denoted by 𝒢1,𝒢2,…​𝒢Γsubscript𝒢1subscript𝒢2…subscript𝒢Γ\mathcal{G}_{1},\mathcal{G}_{2},\dots\mathcal{G}_{\Gamma}. In each group, the users are labeled as user 1 to user K+D+T𝐾𝐷𝑇K+D+T. For simplicity, we refer to user n𝑛n based on its location in a group of users. Without loss of generality, we let γ=⌊n/ν⌋𝛾𝑛𝜈\gamma=\lfloor n/\nu\rfloor+1, and t=nmodν+1𝑡modulo𝑛𝜈1t=n\mod\nu+1, and place user n𝑛n on the t𝑡tth location in group γ𝛾\gamma. Alternatively, we label user n𝑛n using (γ,t)𝛾𝑡(\gamma,t).

2) Arranging the Groups: The groups are arranged on an arbitrary tree, which is called the aggregation tree and denoted by 𝒯​(𝒱^,ℰ^)𝒯^𝒱^ℰ\mathscr{T}(\hat{\mathcal{V}},\hat{\mathcal{E}}). The aggregation tree represents the flow of aggregation. In the aggregation tree, 𝒱^^𝒱\hat{\mathcal{V}} is a set of vertices representing groups and the server, 𝒱^={𝒢1,𝒢2,…,𝒢Γ,Server}^𝒱subscript𝒢1subscript𝒢2…subscript𝒢ΓServer\hat{\mathcal{V}}=\{\mathcal{G}_{1},\mathcal{G}_{2},\dots,\mathcal{G}_{\Gamma},\text{Server}\} and ℰ^^ℰ\hat{\mathcal{E}} is the set of edges representing the active connections between groups. In the aggregation tree, the server is the root and it has only one child which is the last group, 𝒢Γsubscript𝒢Γ\mathcal{G}_{\Gamma}. For example, five different aggregation trees for an example with seven groups of users, 𝒢1,𝒢2,…,𝒢7subscript𝒢1subscript𝒢2…subscript𝒢7\mathcal{G}_{1},\mathcal{G}_{2},\dots,\mathcal{G}_{7} are shown in Fig. 3.

For group 𝒢γsubscript𝒢𝛾\mathcal{G}_{\gamma}, located in one vertex of this tree, let 𝒢γ+subscript𝒢superscript𝛾\mathcal{G}_{\gamma^{+}} represent the parent group of 𝒢γsubscript𝒢𝛾\mathcal{G}_{\gamma}, and ℱ(γ,child)subscriptℱ𝛾child\mathcal{F}_{(\gamma,\text{child})} be the set of indices of its children groups. In a rooted tree, a descendant of group γ𝛾\gamma is any group γ1subscript𝛾1\gamma_{1} whose path from the root contains group γ𝛾\gamma, and group γ2subscript𝛾2\gamma_{2} is an ancestor of group γ𝛾\gamma if and only if group γ𝛾{\gamma} is a descendant of group γ2subscript𝛾2{\gamma_{2}}. Let us define ℱ(γ,desc)subscriptℱ𝛾desc\mathcal{F}_{(\gamma,\text{desc})} as the set of indices of descendant groups of group γ𝛾\gamma, and ℱ(γ,anc)subscriptℱ𝛾anc\mathcal{F}_{(\gamma,\text{anc})} as the set of indices of ancestor groups of group γ𝛾\gamma (excluding the server). For example, in Fig. 3 (d), 𝒢5+=𝒢7subscript𝒢superscript5subscript𝒢7\mathcal{G}_{5^{+}}=\mathcal{G}_{7} is the parent group of 𝒢5subscript𝒢5\mathcal{G}_{5} and ℱ5,child={1,2,3}subscriptℱ5child123\mathcal{F}_{5,\text{child}}=\{1,2,3\}. In addition, 𝒢7subscript𝒢7\mathcal{G}_{7} has set ℱ7,desc={1,2,3,4,5,6}subscriptℱ7desc123456\mathcal{F}_{7,\text{desc}}=\{1,2,3,4,5,6\} and 𝒢1subscript𝒢1\mathcal{G}_{1} has set ℱ1,anc={5,7}subscriptℱ1anc57\mathcal{F}_{1,\text{anc}}=\{5,7\}.

3) Partitioning the Local Models: User n𝑛n partitions its local model into K𝐾K parts, denoted by

𝐖n=[𝐖n,1,𝐖n,2,…,𝐖n,K],subscript𝐖𝑛subscript𝐖𝑛1subscript𝐖𝑛2…subscript𝐖𝑛𝐾\displaystyle\mathbf{W}_{n}=[\mathbf{W}_{n,1},\mathbf{W}_{n,2},\dots,\mathbf{W}_{n,K}], (5)

where each part 𝐖n,k,k∈[K]subscript𝐖𝑛𝑘𝑘delimited-[]𝐾\mathbf{W}_{n,k},k\in[K] is a vector of size of LK𝐿𝐾\frac{L}{K}.

4) Intra-Group Secret Sharing and Aggregation: User n∈[N]𝑛delimited-[]𝑁n\in[N] forms the following polynomial.

𝐅n​(x)=∑k=1K𝐖n,k​xk−1+∑j=1T𝐙n,j​xK+j−1.subscript𝐅𝑛𝑥superscriptsubscript𝑘1𝐾subscript𝐖𝑛𝑘superscript𝑥𝑘1superscriptsubscript𝑗1𝑇subscript𝐙𝑛𝑗superscript𝑥𝐾𝑗1\displaystyle\mathbf{F}_{n}(x)=\sum\limits_{k=1}^{K}\mathbf{W}_{n,k}x^{k-1}+\sum\limits_{j=1}^{T}\mathbf{Z}_{n,j}x^{K+j-1}. (6)

This polynomial function is designed such that the coefficient of xksuperscript𝑥𝑘x^{k} is the (k+1)𝑘1(k+1)th partition of the local model, for k∈[0:K−1]k\in[0:K-1]. Each user n𝑛n uses its polynomial 𝐅n(.)\mathbf{F}_{n}(.) to share its local model with other users.

Let αt∈𝔽psubscript𝛼𝑡subscript𝔽𝑝\alpha_{t}\in\mathbb{F}_{p}, for t∈[ν]𝑡delimited-[]𝜈t\in[\nu], be ν𝜈\nu distinct non-zero constants. We assign αtsubscript𝛼𝑡\alpha_{t} to the t𝑡tth user of all groups, i.e., users (γ,t)𝛾𝑡(\gamma,t), γ=1,…,Γ𝛾1…Γ\gamma=1,\ldots,\Gamma.

Note that in this phase, within each group, at most ν​(ν−1)𝜈𝜈1\nu(\nu-1) communication take place, each of size LK𝐿𝐾\frac{L}{K}.

5) Inter-group Communication and Aggregation: In this phase, user t𝑡t of group γ𝛾\gamma calculates a message denoted by 𝐒(γ,t)subscript𝐒𝛾𝑡\mathbf{S}_{(\gamma,t)} and sends it to user t𝑡t of its parent group γ+superscript𝛾\gamma^{+}, for γ∈[Γ−1]𝛾delimited-[]Γ1\gamma\in[\Gamma-1].

Particularly, if user (γ,t)𝛾𝑡(\gamma,t), γ∈[Γ−1]𝛾delimited-[]Γ1\gamma\in[\Gamma-1] does not have any children groups, i.e., ℱ(γ,child)=∅subscriptℱ𝛾child\mathcal{F}_{(\gamma,\text{child})}=\emptyset, it sets

𝐒(γ,t)=𝐐(γ,t),subscript𝐒𝛾𝑡subscript𝐐𝛾𝑡\displaystyle\mathbf{S}_{(\gamma,t)}=\mathbf{Q}_{(\gamma,t)}, (8)

and sends 𝐒(γ,t)subscript𝐒𝛾𝑡\mathbf{S}_{(\gamma,t)} to user (γ+,t)superscript𝛾𝑡(\gamma^{+},t).

If user (γ,t)𝛾𝑡(\gamma,t) does not receive 𝐒(γ−,t)subscript𝐒superscript𝛾𝑡\mathbf{S}_{(\gamma^{-},t)} from at least one group in ℱ(γ,child)subscriptℱ𝛾child\mathcal{F}_{(\gamma,\text{child})}, it also remains silent for the rest of the protocol. In this phase, at most ν​(Γ−1)𝜈Γ1\nu(\Gamma-1) messages are communicated, each of size LK𝐿𝐾\frac{L}{K}. 6) Communication with the Server: User t𝑡t of the last group, i.e., user (Γ,t)Γ𝑡(\Gamma,t) computes

𝐒(Γ,t)=𝐐(Γ,t)+∑γ−∈ℱ(Γ,child)𝐒(γ−,t),subscript𝐒Γ𝑡subscript𝐐Γ𝑡subscriptsuperscript𝛾subscriptℱΓchildsubscript𝐒superscript𝛾𝑡\displaystyle\mathbf{S}_{(\Gamma,t)}=\mathbf{Q}_{(\Gamma,t)}+\sum\limits_{\gamma^{-}\in\mathcal{F}_{(\Gamma,\text{child})}}\mathbf{S}_{(\gamma^{-},t)}, (10)

and sends it to the server, for t∈[ν]𝑡delimited-[]𝜈t\in[\nu].

Remark 5:

In (6), we use ramp sharing [17] to keep individual local models private, but any other arbitrary T𝑇T-private MDS code can be used for 𝐅n​(x)subscript𝐅𝑛𝑥\mathbf{F}_{n}(x). Ramp sharing allows us to reduce the size of shares and consequently achieve the cut-set outer bound within a diminishing gap.

Remark 6:

The formation of the groups and the topology of the aggregation tree in SwiftAgg+ may be constrained by the actual connectivity in the network.

In particular, for any user (γ,t)𝛾𝑡(\gamma,t) in 𝒟𝒟\mathcal{D}, 𝐒(Γ,t)​(αt)subscript𝐒Γ𝑡subscript𝛼𝑡\mathbf{S}_{(\Gamma,t)}(\alpha_{t}) is null. Thus at most D𝐷D users in the last group send null messages to the server. Since the size of each group is D+T+K𝐷𝑇𝐾D+T+K, the server receives at least T+K𝑇𝐾T+K values 𝐒(Γ,t)​(αt)subscript𝐒Γ𝑡subscript𝛼𝑡\mathbf{S}_{(\Gamma,t)}(\alpha_{t}) for distinct αtsubscript𝛼𝑡\alpha_{t}, and thus can correctly recover 𝐅​(x)𝐅𝑥\mathbf{F}(x).

VI Theoretical Analysis

In this section, we analyze the communication and computation complexities of the proposed SwiftAgg+ scheme, and provide an information-theoretic proof on its privacy guarantee in protecting local model information from colluding users and the server.

VI-A Communication Loads and Number of Active Connections

According to (12), the total number of symbols that are needed to be received by the server is T+K𝑇𝐾T+K, each of size LK𝐿𝐾\frac{L}{K}. Thus, the normalized server communication load in SwiftAgg+ is Rserver(L)=1+TK.superscriptsubscript𝑅server𝐿1𝑇𝐾R_{\text{server}}^{(L)}=1+\frac{T}{K}.

In each group, at most ν​(ν−1)𝜈𝜈1\nu(\nu-1) symbols are sent by the members, each of size LK𝐿𝐾\frac{L}{K}, and there are Nν𝑁𝜈\frac{N}{\nu} groups. In addition, at most ν𝜈\nu symbols are sent from a child group to a parent group. Thus, the normalized per-user communication load in SwiftAgg+ is upper-bounded as Ruser(L)≤(1+T+DK)superscriptsubscript𝑅user𝐿1𝑇𝐷𝐾R_{\text{user}}^{(L)}\leq(1+\frac{T+D}{K}), and the number of active communication links in the communication graph of SwiftAgg+, i.e., |ℰSwiftAgg+|subscriptℰSwiftAgg+|\mathcal{E}_{\texttt{SwiftAgg+}}|, is upper bounded by Nν​(ν​(ν−1)2+ν)=N2​(K+T+D+1)𝑁𝜈𝜈𝜈12𝜈𝑁2𝐾𝑇𝐷1\frac{N}{\nu}\left(\frac{\nu(\nu-1)}{2}+\nu\right)=\frac{N}{2}(K+T+D+1).

It is clear that through adjusting the value of K𝐾K between 111 and N−D−T𝑁𝐷𝑇N-D-T, we can have a trade-off between the communication loads and the number of active connections in the network. One choice of interest is K=N−D−T𝐾𝑁𝐷𝑇K=N-D-T as the largest value for K𝐾K, which leads to Theorem 1 and minimizes the communication loads. It is also possible to minimize the number of network connections by choosing K=1𝐾1K=1, as proposed in [14].

While the communication loads and the number of active communication links are determined by the value of K𝐾K using SwiftAgg+, the actual communication delay of the model aggregation also depends on the topology of the adopted aggregation tree. Assume that each communication link between two groups has maximum delay δIntersubscript𝛿Inter\delta_{\text{Inter}}. In the case of more than one group, the total delay of each training iteration, ΔΔ\Delta, can be minimized if ℱ(Γ,child)={γ1,γ2,…,Γ−1}subscriptℱΓchildsubscript𝛾1subscript𝛾2…Γ1\mathcal{F}_{(\Gamma,\text{child})}=\{\gamma_{1},\gamma_{2},\dots,\Gamma-1\}. Thus, in a synchronous system Δ=2​δInter+δIntraΔ2subscript𝛿Intersubscript𝛿Intra\Delta=2\delta_{\text{Inter}}+\delta_{\text{Intra}}, where δIntrasubscript𝛿Intra\delta_{\text{Intra}} is the delay for intra-group communications. This case is shown for an example consisting of 7 groups in Fig. 3(e). In contrast, the maximum delay occurs when the groups are located sequentially in the aggregation tree which is shown for the example in Fig. 3(a), and Δ=Γ​δInter+δIntraΔΓsubscript𝛿Intersubscript𝛿Intra\Delta=\Gamma\delta_{\text{Inter}}+\delta_{\text{Intra}}.

VI-B Computation Loads

In this subsection, we analyze the computation loads at the server and at each user with respect to the maximum number semi-honest users, T𝑇T, maximum number of dropouts, D𝐷D, and size of the local models, L𝐿L, and the design parameter 1≤K≤N−T−D1𝐾𝑁𝑇𝐷1\leq K\leq N-T-D that is the number of sub-vectors each local model is broken into.

Computational Complexity at the Server: In SwiftAgg+, to recover the aggregation of local models, the server needs to receive T+K𝑇𝐾T+K outcomes of the users in the last group, each of size LK𝐿𝐾\frac{L}{K}. Therefore, the computation performed by the server includes interpolation of a polynomial of degree T+K−1𝑇𝐾1T+K-1, where the coefficients are vectors of size LK𝐿𝐾\frac{L}{K}. The complexity of interpolation of a polynomial of degree d𝑑d is 𝒪​(d​log2⁡d)𝒪𝑑superscript2𝑑\mathcal{O}(d\log^{2}d), when the field supports FFT [18]. Thus, the computational complexity at the server is 𝒪​((1+T−1K)​L​log2⁡(K+T−1))𝒪1𝑇1𝐾𝐿superscript2𝐾𝑇1\mathcal{O}\big{(}(1+\frac{T-1}{K})L\log^{2}(K+T-1)\big{)}.

Computational Complexity at the User: In SwiftAgg+, each user performs the following two operations:

  1. 1.

    It evaluates one polynomial in ν=K+T+D𝜈𝐾𝑇𝐷\nu=K+T+D distinct values. If the field supports FFT, evaluation of a polynomial function of degree d𝑑d has a computational complexity of 𝒪​(log2⁡d)𝒪superscript2𝑑\mathcal{O}(\log^{2}d) [18]. In SwiftAgg+, we need to compute one polynomial of degree T+K−1𝑇𝐾1T+K-1, where the coefficients are vectors of size LK𝐿𝐾\frac{L}{K}, at ν𝜈\nu points. Thus, this step requires a complexity of 𝒪​((T+K+D)​LK​log2⁡(T+K−1))𝒪𝑇𝐾𝐷𝐿𝐾superscript2𝑇𝐾1\mathcal{O}\big{(}(T+K+D)\frac{L}{K}\log^{2}{(T+K-1)}\big{)}.

  2. 2.

    On average each user computes the summation of ν+1𝜈1\nu+1 vectors of size LK𝐿𝐾\frac{L}{K} which has a complexity of 𝒪​((T+K+D)​LK)𝒪𝑇𝐾𝐷𝐿𝐾\mathcal{O}\big{(}(T+K+D)\frac{L}{K}\big{)}.

Therefore, the computation load on each user is 𝒪​((1+T+DK)​L​(1+log2⁡(T+K−1)))𝒪1𝑇𝐷𝐾𝐿1superscript2𝑇𝐾1\mathcal{O}\big{(}(1+\frac{T+D}{K}){L}(1+\log^{2}(T+K-1))\big{)}.

VI-E Proof of Privacy

In this section, we prove that SwiftAgg+ satisfies the privacy constraint in (II). The privacy must be guaranteed even if the server colludes with any set 𝒯⊂[N]𝒯delimited-[]𝑁\mathcal{T}\subset[N] of at most T𝑇T semi-honest users which can distribute arbitrary across the groups. At a high level, we expand the mutual information in (II) over the groups containing the semi-honest users, from the leaf to the root of the aggregation tree, and show that model privacy will be preserved at each expansion step.

In SwiftAgg+, the Intra-group Secret Sharing is inspired by ramp secret sharing scheme [17]. Ramp secret sharing scheme is proposed to reduce the size of shares in Shamir’s secret sharing [15]. It proposes a trade-off between security and size of the shares. In ramp sharing scheme with T𝑇T-privacy, no information can be leaked from any T𝑇T or less shares. This directly leads to the following corollary for SwiftAgg+.

VII conclusion

In this paper, we propose SwiftAgg+, a secure aggregation protocol for model aggregation in federated learning, which acheives a trade-off between the communication loads and network connections. Via partitioning the users into groups, careful designs of intra and inter group secret sharing and aggregation method, SwiftAgg+ is able to achieve correct aggregation in presence of up to D𝐷D dropout users, with the worst-case security guarantee against up to T𝑇T users colluding with a curious server. Moreover, SwiftAgg+ has a flexibility to control the delay of each training iteration by choosing the aggregation tree with different depth. Compared with previous secure aggregation protocols, SwiftAgg+ significantly slashes the communication load. For T=o​(N)𝑇𝑜𝑁T=o(N) and N−D=𝒪​(N)𝑁𝐷𝒪𝑁N-D=\mathcal{O}(N), in terms of the number of required bits, the server communication load in SwiftAgg+ is within factor 1 of the cut-set lower bound. In addition, in the case of local models with uniform distributions, the per-user communication load in SwiftAgg+ is within factor logℓ⁡ℓ​Nsubscriptℓℓ𝑁\log_{\ell}{\ell N} of the cut-set lower bound as long as T=o​(N)𝑇𝑜𝑁T=o(N) and D=o​(N)𝐷𝑜𝑁D=o(N).
